[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'AI is changing the creative industries forever. Actors and content creators are using AI to replace themselves or even come back from the dead. AI-generated songs are topping the music charts and AI avatars are even delivering speeches to world leaders in Switzerland. Now,'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is happening so fast that you might not even realize some of the ways AI is seeping into reality. We\'re going to go through 15 real examples of how AI is affecting creative industries right now.'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, this ranges from the quietly useful all the way through to the genuinely disturbing. And I\'ll tell you up front now, one of those examples is hidden inside this video itself. But, we\'ll get to that later. If you\'re new here, I\'m'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'AI Samson. Old 4x3 TV footage looked fine on a 1980s CRT. On a modern 65-in 4K screen, it looks completely broken. Not because the footage degraded, but because the screen\'s got better and the footage'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'didn\'t. It means that some of the greatest cinema from previous eras cannot be truly enjoyed. But now, AI restoration tools can now analyze the footage frame by frame and actually synthesize new pixels that were never'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there. They\'re not stretching or cropping, but they\'re predicting what would have been in the shot when applied to a 16x9 frame. When applied to this old footage, we can not only add more detail and turn black and white footage'

[01:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into color, but we can also extend it from 4x3 into 16x9 widescreen. Now, some interesting applications that you could do with this is that you could take old out-of-copyright footage and upscale it, extend it, and colorize it,'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then you can release these or create this as an offering to others either to gain an audience or to earn some income. You could also take any old family footage from your'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'own archives and restore them as gifts for loved ones. This is particularly moving for those in older generations who are trying to remember parts of their past to be able to see them in new ways. Now, the idea there is putting old things back together, but what happens'

[01:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if we take this further and try to use old influences to create entirely new media. For example, Val Kilmer lost his voice to throat cancer in 2014, and when Top Gun: Maverick needed him back as'

[02:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Iceman, instead of writing him out, the filmmakers partnered with a London-based startup Sonantic. They fed hours of Kilmer\'s archival recordings into a neural network that literally learned to speak like him. They generated over 40'

[02:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different voice models and picked the best one. Kilmer\'s daughter confirmed they were able to dub him with his own voice. It\'s such a technical feat. Now, at the time this might have felt like a one-off'

[02:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'miracle for a beloved actor. Now, 3 years later, the exact same technology is consumer-grade and available to everyone, and I will now even play you a small clip of my own AI voice generated via ElevenLabs. Hello, this is the'

